    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup for LawDog hinges on capitalizing on soft matchups against middle-of-the-road starters. **Cal Raleigh** (70.13) and **Geraldo Perdomo** (69.13) stand out as our elite anchors today. **Perdomo** benefits significantly from the matchup against M\u00e1rquez (5.26 xERA) and an ideal leadoff spot, while **Raleigh** enjoys a massive boost from a favorable platoon advantage against Liberatore. **Bryson Stott** (66.28) is another high-floor play, leveraging a strong platoon edge against Elder. While **Taylor Ward** faces a challenge in Crochet (2.86 xERA), the park factors are heavily in his favor, maintaining his \"Strong\" status (59.23) despite the elite opposing arm.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Drew Gilbert**, who hovered near our active threshold at 43.86. While **Gilbert** benefits from Eury P\u00e9rez\u2019s slow delivery\u2014providing a theoretical boost to his stolen base potential\u2014the optimizer ultimately favored the higher projected efficiency and lineup positioning of our active bats like **Gavin Sheets** and **Jung Hoo Lee**. Elsewhere, we are exercising caution with **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez**; despite his raw talent, the combination of facing Gausman (3.79 xERA) and a poor BvP history suppresses his expectation, though he remains a mandatory start due to his pedigree. \n\nRisk management remains paramount today, particularly with **Daulton Varsho** and **Jeremiah Jackson**. Both players are projected to be marginal starts (45.72) primarily because they draw the tough assignment of Crochet; their scores are kept afloat only by favorable park dynamics. We will be monitoring the late-afternoon weather and any final lineup shifts, particularly for those players who historically drift down the order. We are keeping **Lawrence Butler** and others on the bench, prioritizing our current lineup's efficiency as we push to secure gains in the scarce stolen base category.",
